<subSubSection type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="38" pageNumber="1495" type="mainText">
Note: In the MNHP, Paris, there is one cotype (worker) with five mandibular teeth, the apical not much longer than the subapical, a tubular first maxillary palp segment and a distinct reticulate sculpture on the head and alitrunk. This combination of characters diagnoses ants of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dlussky" authorityYear="1969" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Alloformica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Alloformica</taxonomicName>
(Agosti, in preparation). The emarginate occiput, which is unique within Profomica, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dlussky" authorityYear="1969" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Alloformica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Alloformica</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Cataglyphis" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Cataglyphis</taxonomicName>
, separates 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Agosti" authorityYear="1990" baseAuthorityName="Kusnetzov-Ugamskij" baseAuthorityYear="1990" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Alloformica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">flavicornis</taxonomicName>
from the two other species within 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dlussky" authorityYear="1969" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Alloformica" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Alloformica</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
